# FitPulse — Fitness Dashboard Implementation Plan

> This is an **example** implementation plan generated from the AI Implementation Prompt.  
> It demonstrates the level of detail and format the AI should produce.  
> Use this as a reference when reviewing AI-generated plans.

---

## Overview

FitPulse is a modern fitness tracking dashboard web application. It provides a visually engaging interface for users to track workouts, monitor progress, and view health metrics. The target audience is fitness enthusiasts who want a premium, data-rich experience without backend complexity. All data is client-side mock data — this is a frontend showcase.

Key differentiators: fluid dark-mode-first UI, animated data visualizations, responsive card-based layout, and a design that feels like a native app rather than a typical web dashboard.

---

## Tech Stack

### Core
| Package | Version | Command | Reason |
|---------|---------|---------|--------|
| Next.js | latest (16.x) | `npx -y create-next-app@latest fitpulse --typescript --tailwind --eslint --app --src-dir --use-npm --yes` | App Router, built-in optimization, server components |
| React | 19.x | (included) | UI library |
| TypeScript | 5.x | (included) | Type safety |
| Tailwind CSS | v4 | (included) | CSS-first utility styling |
| Framer Motion | latest | `npm install framer-motion` | Declarative animations, scroll-linked motion |
| Recharts | latest | `npm install recharts` | Lightweight chart library for fitness data |

### What NOT to use
- **GSAP**: Framer Motion covers all animation needs; adding GSAP doubles the animation bundle
- **Chart.js**: Recharts integrates better with React and supports responsive SVG charts
- **Zustand/Redux**: Overkill for this scope — React context + useState is sufficient
- **CSS Modules**: Tailwind handles everything; modules add unnecessary file overhead

